The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is to adopt the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already provides interfaces and test helpers.

## Setup

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

## Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

## Inject into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Write(string path, string content) => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path) => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

## Test with MockFileSystem

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

// ReadAllText works against the in-memory filesystem
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Read("/data/config.json"));

// WriteAllText writes to the mock
service.Write("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

// Directory.Exists checks the mock
Assert.True(mockFs.Directory.Exists("/data"));
```

## Migration summary

1. Install the NuGet packages above.
2. Register `IFileSystem` in your DI container.
3. Replace constructor-local `File.*` / `Directory.*` calls with `fileSystem.File.*` / `fileSystem.Directory.*`.
4. In tests, pass a `MockFileSystem` — no disk I/O needed.

